comment:
 @faceurhell  It's not even all of them at the root of the problem. Almost all of the memory and NAND chips for RAM and SSDs are made by three companies (Micron, Samsung, SK Hynix), and all three of them decided to shift all of their production capacity to chips used for enterprise products, then choose to sell all of it to companies building AI data centers.

Companies like Corsair, Kingston, and Western Digital can't even get the chips needed to make their consumer products. Samsung's fabrication arm actually refused to provide stock to Samsung's own mobile development division, and Micron completely shuttered their consumer products division (Crucial). So every company and customer are now fighting over the scraps leftover from last year's production runs.

Imagine if Ford, GM, and Stellantis all got together and plotted to stop making every consumer vehicle, and devoted every factory to only building commercial vans/trucks. Then chose to only sell those to large corporations operating fleets of them. Dealerships would empty out and have no new cars to replace them with. The rest is supply and demand at work.

 @cranehawk  yes, a product that was $149 going up by $100 overnight is an insane price increase.

67% increase. 

I’ve never seen anything like it in my life.
